ir language of testimony was Yiddish, English, or Hebrew. The differences between their testimonies relate to notions of love, justice, community-and how the Holocaust did violence to these aspects of the self. More than an original presentation of yet-unheard stories, this book challenges the assumption of a universal vocabulary for describing and healing human pain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aHolocaust survivors. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xHistoriography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xSources. 0aOral history. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2018z978311063899840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300235531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300235531.jpg  a978-3-11-063899-8  YUP eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles